---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is a systemd timer?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'A systemd timer is a scheduling unit in Linux that triggers a service using calendar or monotonic timing rules.'
      }
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I use systemd timer vs cron?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Use systemd timers when you want better service integration, startup catch-up with Persistent=true, and easier logging with journald.'
      }
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How do I enable a timer?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Create the .service and .timer files, then run sudo systemctl daemon-reload and sudo systemctl enable --now your-name.timer.'
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="Systemd Timer Generator" description="Generate systemd timer and service units for Linux automation schedules.">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="muted">Linux Dork Tools</p>
    <h1>Systemd Timer Generator</h1>
    <p>Create a production-friendly systemd timer and service pair in seconds.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card prose">
    <h2>Why use systemd timers for Linux automation?</h2>
    <p>
      A systemd timer is a modern scheduling method on Linux that can replace many cron jobs. It links directly to a
      named service unit, which makes execution behavior explicit and easier to maintain over time.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you are deciding between cron vs systemd timer, timers usually provide stronger lifecycle control.
      You can inspect failures with systemctl status, review logs in journald, and tune service settings without
      editing one-line crontab entries.
    </p>
    <p>
      Timers are also useful for machines that reboot often. With <code>Persistent=true</code>, missed runs can be caught
      after startup, which helps prevent skipped backup or cleanup jobs on laptops, edge hosts, and small servers.
    </p>
    <p>
      This generator creates copy-ready unit content so you can move from schedule idea to a running Linux timer quickly,
      while still following maintainable systemd conventions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Service settings</h2>
    <div class="grid">
      <label>Service name <input id="svc-name" value="backup-home" /></label>
      <label>Command <input id="svc-command" value="/usr/local/bin/backup-home.sh" /></label>
      <label>Run schedule
        <select id="schedule">
          <option value="hourly">Hourly</option>
          <option value="daily" selected>Daily</option>
          <option value="weekly">Weekly</option>
          <option value="weekdays">Weekdays</option>
        </select>
      </label>
      <label>Time (HH:MM) <input id="time" value="02:30" /></label>
    </div>
    <p class="muted">Tip: timers add startup catch-up and better journald logging than classic cron.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Generated <code>.service</code></h2>
    <pre id="service-output"></pre>
    <h2>Generated <code>.timer</code></h2>
    <pre id="timer-output"></pre>
    <p id="enable-output" class="muted"></p>
    <pre>Preview
OnCalendar=*-*-* 02:30:00
sudo systemctl enable --now backup-home.timer</pre>
  </section>

  <script src="../../scripts/systemd-timer-generator.ts"></script>
  <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)}></script>

  <style>
    .prose p { margin: 0.75rem 0; }
    .grid { display:grid; gap:.65rem; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit,minmax(220px,1fr)); }
    label { display:grid; gap:.35rem; font-weight:600; }
    input, select { border:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--surface); color:var(--text); border-radius:.55rem; padding:.6rem .7rem; font:inherit; }
    pre { margin:0 0 1rem; background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:.65rem; padding:.75rem; white-space:pre-wrap; overflow:auto; }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
